		<header class="story-header">
		<h1 itemprop="headline" class="story-heading entry-title"><span>Susan Faludi: &#8216;In My World, Photographs Lie&#8217;</span></h1>		<div class="story-meta entry-meta">
			<span class="author vcard byline-author"
					itemscope=""
					itemprop="author creator"
					itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
					By <span class="fn" itemprop="name">Susan Faludi</span>
				</span><!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2017-05-16T08:00:57+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">May. 16, 2017</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">May. 16, 2017</span><span class="postMetaHeaderCommentCount commentCount hidden">
					<i class="icon"></i>
					<a class="commentCountLink commentCountNumberOnly" href="//lens.blogs.nytimes.com/2017/05/16/susan-faludi-in-my-world-photographs-lie/"></a>
				</span>		</div>
	</header>
	<div class="shareTools sharetools layout-vertical" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//lens.blogs.nytimes.com/2017/05/16/susan-faludi-in-my-world-photographs-lie/" data-title="Susan Faludi: &#8216;In My World, Photographs Lie&#8217;" data-description="Susan Faludi&#039;s latest book, about her photographer father&#039;s transition to a woman, originally had no photos. In time she realized that images are moments carved disingenuously out of continuous experience, but they can be redeemed by age."><div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div></div>	<div class="post-content">
				<script>
			if ( window.innerWidth < 975 ) {
				document.write( '<div class="module ad" id="MiddleRight"></div>' );
			}
		</script>
		<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My father, Stefanie Faludi, died just before dawn on May 14, 2015, in the womanâs ward of a Budapest hospital, at the age of 87. It had been 11 years since her sex reassignment surgery and, not coincidentally, 11 years since our reunion after a quarter-century of estrangement. In the days after her death, I combed through her house, a forbidding concrete bunker perched high in the Buda Hills, inspecting the many closets, cabinets and storerooms sheâd kept locked. I was looking for a clue to a life just passed, an inkling of who she was. Under the eaves behind two sets of deadbolts, and tucked inside steel cases, storage bins and acetate envelopes, I discovered an arsenal of cameras &#8211; Hasselblad, Rolleiflex, Leica, Olympus, a bellows camera built into a mahogany frame &#8211; lenses, cables, filters, tripods, along with developing sinks and processing trays, a wall-mounted enlarger and giant drum print-dryer, relics of her commercial photo business in Manhattan in the 1980s, her documentary work of the Brazilian interior in the 1950s, and her first attempts at filmmaking in Hungary in the 1930s. And, in acetate envelopes and slide trays, thousands of Tri-X negatives and Ektachrome slides, along with contact sheets and prints, chronicling year by year and in meticulous order, the minutiae of Faludi family life. That is: my life, and my life with my father. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Yet, a year later, when I published the book that she had invited me to write, a book about her, there was not a photo in it. Plenty of words, my words, tens of thousands of them, including many describing photographs of and by my father, but none of the images themselves. Readers asked: How could I write a portrait of a photographer and not include a single photograph? By withholding the pictures, one correspondent wrote, I had kept my readership âin the dark.â I defended myself with explanations: I didnât want to cramp readersâ imaginations, I didnât want to abet the voyeurism that greets some transgender memoirs. I feared photographyâs power to obliterate the reality of the actual person. (âBecause of the many pictures I have of my father,â Sally Mann mourned in Hold Still, âhe eludes me completely.â) I recited all those reasons. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But I left out the biggest one: In my world, photographs lie. </p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/15/blogs/16-lens-faludi-embed1/16-lens-faludi-embed1-blog480-v2.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/15/blogs/16-lens-faludi-embed1/16-lens-faludi-embed1-blog480-v2.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/15/blogs/16-lens-faludi-embed1/16-lens-faludi-embed1-blog480-v2.jpg" id="100000005099365" width="480" height="528" alt="IstvÃ¡n Friedman (later Steven Faludi) as a young auteur. Early 1950s." class="media-viewer-candidate" data-mediaviewer-src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/15/blogs/16-lens-faludi-embed1/16-lens-faludi-embed1-superJumbo-v2.jpg" data-mediaviewer-caption="IstvÃ¡n Friedman (later Steven Faludi) as a young auteur. Early 1950s." data-mediaviewer-credit="Courtesy of Susan Faludi" /><meta itemprop="height" content="528"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">IstvÃ¡n Friedman (later Steven Faludi) as a young auteur. Early 1950s.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Courtesy of Susan Faludi</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Among the piles of prints and slides in my fatherâs repository were snapshots of us when she was still Steve Faludi, all-American (albeit immigrant) dad, and I, his not-so-dutiful daughter. Here we are as a family, bicycling through upstate New York on our 10-speed Schwinns, hiking up Bear Mountain in matching 60/40 parkas, dining on burgers on our imitation-redwood deck, sunbathing in webbed lawn chairs on our quarter-acre yard, gathered around the TV in our faux-Colonial tract home. Here is the intact model, the two-parent, two-child, one-dog nuclear unit, forever and cheerfully displaying its normalcy before the camera.  I scour these pictures for some sign, beneath the scrim of family cheer, of the misery I remember. Where in these images are my fatherâs tirades, our fearful silences, the white-knuckled car trips, the broken furniture, the bloodstains in the carpet? Where is any premonition of our bitter estrangement, of his violence or of his evolution into her? The voluminous collection bears no trace. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âAll of the photographs in our family album were built on some kind of lie about who we were, and revealed a truth about who we wanted to be,â Richard Avedon wrote of the snapshots taken by his father, Jacob Israel Avedon. âWe made compositions. We dressed up. We posed in front of expensive cars, homes that weren&#8217;t ours. . . .There we were in front of canopies and Packards with borrowed dogs, and always, forever, smiling.â </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">His lament could have been my own. With all the disagreements between me and my father over the years, and they were many and serious, the fundamental one became the distinction between the parent who would use the irrefutable image to gloss over the truth of things and the daughter who put her faith in the ever-flexible word to reclaim that truth. Maybe my prose-only book was meant as a victory in our historic war. Never mind that she had asked me to write it; the finished work gave me, as it were, the final word. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But as the months went by, doubts crept in. The battle line no longer felt so cleanly drawn. My triumph seemed hollow. In short, I changed my mind. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When &#8220;In the Darkroom&#8221; came out in paperback this May, it had photographs.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">During my fatherâs career in New York from the 1960s to the late 1980s, he was sought out for what he called âtrick photography.â Steve Faludi was a master of manipulative techniques &#8211; the montage, the composite, the color conversion, dodging, masking, burning, and the other transmutations of the pre-Photoshop trade. He had built a career on altering images. CondÃ© Nast turned to him to perform the most difficult darkroom mutations for its coffee table books and publications, Vanity Fair, Vogue, Glamour, House &#038; Gardens, Brides. He worked with many leading commercial photographers of the day, among them: Francesco Scavullo, Irving Penn, and Bert Stern. Also: Avedon.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">By the time I came to Budapest, my fatherâs âtrick photographyâ had found a new application. In our family pictures, Steve had been mostly behind the camera. In her new photographs, documenting her gender transformation, StefÃ¡nie was in front, the woman in the frame. Her home computer held thousands of selfies and self-montages of her in the guise of fashion model, beauty contestant, movie actress, Danish princess, Hungarian csÃ¡rdÃ¡s folk dancer, permutations of what she called her ânew self.â </p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/15/blogs/16-lens-faludi-embed2/16-lens-faludi-embed2-blog480-v2.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/15/blogs/16-lens-faludi-embed2/16-lens-faludi-embed2-blog480-v2.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/15/blogs/16-lens-faludi-embed2/16-lens-faludi-embed2-blog480-v2.jpg" id="100000005099373" width="480" height="321" alt="Documentation of the Brazilian landscape. 1950s." class="media-viewer-candidate" data-mediaviewer-src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/15/blogs/16-lens-faludi-embed2/16-lens-faludi-embed2-superJumbo-v2.jpg" data-mediaviewer-caption="Documentation of the Brazilian landscape. 1950s." data-mediaviewer-credit="Stefanie Faludi" /><meta itemprop="height" content="321"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Documentation of the Brazilian landscape. 1950s.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Stefanie Faludi</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âNewâ seemed the giveaway, as though a self, that continuing and gradually accruing essence, could be segmented into chapters, with each new chapter leaving behind the last. Where was her history? Her personal heritage? Her childhood growing up in Budapest as the privileged only son of well-to-do assimilated Hungarian Jews, or her trials during WWII, when he&#8217;d been a fugitive urchin on the streets of Budapest? Her postwar years in Brazil, chronicling the vast outback for the Brazilian geographic institute? She&#8217;d banished it all. The vast digital chronicle of StefÃ¡nieâs new persona seemed less story than screenshot, more poster than movie. âI&#8217;m another person now,â she told me as we looked though her portfolio. It seemed to me that the ethic of the photograph conspired in this disconnect, a method for recording the past serving to ostracize it. When I returned home after one of those early visits, I read John Bergerâs âAnother Way of Telling,â and was struck by this: âWhereas remembered images are the residue of continuous experience, a photograph isolates the appearances of a disconnected instant.â </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For a dozen years, between our rapprochement and my fatherâs death, I tried to piece together the âcontinuous experienceâ of her life, an experience rooted in the larger history of a family and sprung from the rubble of the Austro-Hungarian Empire. I spent hundreds of hours interviewing archivists, historians, my fatherâs old schoolmates, neighbors, co-religionists and, most of all, the surviving relatives of our extended family, the family my father had cut himself off from sixty years earlier, when he changed his name from IstvÃ¡n Friedman to Steven Faludi. I made the rounds of the remnants of the Hungarian and Slovak Friedman-GrÃ¼nberger clan, a diaspora dispersed to Basel and Prague, Tel Aviv and Netanya and Kfar Saba, New York, Washington D.C., Michigan and Sydney, Australia. I was after their remembered images, the ones lodged in the mindâs eye, the ones I believed could only be unearthed through long and probing conversation. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And yet, for all the interview tapes I transcribed, for all the words I compiled in  notebooks, I seemed no closer to grasping the fundaments of my fatherâs grapple.  All I had were insufficient words, and a houseful of slides that presented a past I knew to be a concoction. I didn&#8217;t yet perceive that it would be photographs that would guide my prose to shore, that there was another and more revelatory side to the images I&#8217;d learned to distrust.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI see what you&#8217;re doing,â my father said to me one day as I pressed her for details. Her sharp eyes appraised me. âJust what Avedon did.â She was recalling photographs sheâd first seen in Avedonâs studio in the early 1970s. âThose pictures of his father,â my father said. âThey were frightening.â With excruciating clarity and under unforgiving light, Avedon had chronicled Jacob Israelâs long and terrible surrender to cancer. He had hoped the project might bring them closer; father and son had been estranged for many years. But when Jacob Israel saw the portraits, Avedon recalled, he was âwounded.â The son tried to explain his intent in a letter: âWhen you pose for a photograph, itâs behind a smile that isnât yours. You are angry and hungry and alive. What I value in you is that intensity. . . .Do you understand?â (Avedon later found the letter in the pocket of a suit his father never wore.) </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The photographs my father saw in Avedon&#8217;s studio were intended as rebuttal to the duplicitous family snapshots Avedon had grown up with. The prose in my book had the same aim. Yet, in the course of writing it, I discovered a contrary dynamic: the ways dishonest photographs, moments carved disingenuously out of continuous experience, can be redeemed by age.</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/15/blogs/16-lens-faludi-embed3/16-lens-faludi-embed3-blog480-v2.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/15/blogs/16-lens-faludi-embed3/16-lens-faludi-embed3-blog480-v2.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/15/blogs/16-lens-faludi-embed3/16-lens-faludi-embed3-blog480-v2.jpg" id="100000005099380" width="480" height="371" alt="Julius GrÃ¼nberger and friends in the Hungarian countryside. 1930s." class="media-viewer-candidate" data-mediaviewer-src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/15/blogs/16-lens-faludi-embed3/16-lens-faludi-embed3-superJumbo-v2.jpg" data-mediaviewer-caption="Julius GrÃ¼nberger and friends in the Hungarian countryside. 1930s." data-mediaviewer-credit="Courtesy of Susan Faludi" /><meta itemprop="height" content="371"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Julius GrÃ¼nberger and friends in the Hungarian countryside. 1930s.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Courtesy of Susan Faludi</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On a beastly hot summer day in Kfar Saba, Israel, a second cousin Iâd only met the day before opened a cardboard box in her air-conditioned living room and poured its contents onto her coffee table: scores of snapshots. She pulled out one after another at random and handed them to me: a glamorous couple dancing in formal evening wear. Two young fashionable men in knickerbockers and oiled hair joking beside a gleaming roadster. Skiers in silk scarfs grinning from a mountaintop. Here were faces of a family I&#8217;d never met, the extended Friedman/GrÃ¼nberger clan. In one home or another, on one continent or another, as I interviewed one relative or another, the ritual repeated. At some point, the host would leave the room and return with a manila envelope, a plastic bag or a cardboard box, and shake out onto a table the booty they contained. The interviews Iâd pursued to get beneath the artifice of photographs kept ending up in photographs.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The black-and-white snapshots showcased women in furs and heels, men with walking canes and watch fobs, posing at the spas, beach resorts, ski lodges, and five-star hotels of interwar Europe. The glamorous GrÃ¼nberger girls &#8211; my grandmother Rozi and her three sisters &#8211; dance and shop across the capitals of Central Europe. A dapper gentleman with a cleft chin, looking sharp in a tailored suit and fedora, strolls along a boardwalk in the Czech spa town of Carlsbad in 1937, treks with friends in the High Tatras, and poses in a landscaped backyard with his wife in folk costume, his daughter in braids and bows: ÃrpÃ¡d, my great-uncle, who ran the family lumber business with my great-grandfather, Leopold GrÃ¼nberger, the family patriarch. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In a faux-alligator-leather-bound album, its curled contents coming unstuck from heavy black pages: photographs of my grandparentsâ âsecond honeymoon,â a 1936 Mediterranean cruise on the luxury liner Palestina. A  woman in checked skirt, low heels and a fashionable brimmed cap waits dockside to board a ship in Genoa, tours the ruins in Alexandria, rides a camel past the Great Sphinx of Giza: my grandmother Rozi. I knew enough of family lore to spot the dishonesty in these particular celebratory shots; just outside the frame of domestic harmony lay accusation and betrayal, a neglected only son, a relationship disintegrating. The marriage would not long outlive its second honeymoon.</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/16/blogs/16-lens-faludi-embed5/16-lens-faludi-embed5-blog480-v2.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/16/blogs/16-lens-faludi-embed5/16-lens-faludi-embed5-blog480-v2.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/16/blogs/16-lens-faludi-embed5/16-lens-faludi-embed5-blog480-v2.jpg" id="100000005099449" width="480" height="451" alt="Rozi Friedman, Susan Faludi&#039;s grandmother, onboard the Palestina for a Mediterranean cruise. 1936." class="media-viewer-candidate" data-mediaviewer-src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/16/blogs/16-lens-faludi-embed5/16-lens-faludi-embed5-superJumbo-v2.jpg" data-mediaviewer-caption="Rozi Friedman, Susan Faludi&#039;s grandmother, onboard the Palestina for a Mediterranean cruise. 1936." data-mediaviewer-credit="Courtesy of Susan Faludi" /><meta itemprop="height" content="451"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Rozi Friedman, Susan Faludi's grandmother, onboard the Palestina for a Mediterranean cruise. 1936.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Courtesy of Susan Faludi</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Friedman-GrÃ¼nberger photographs were more profoundly deceitful than that. They were self-conscious demonstrations of a successful Jewish assimilation into Christian Magyar society, as eager and aspirational as my father&#8217;s American suburban scenes or Jacob Israelâs family snaps or StefÃ¡nie caught mid-whirl in an embroidered csÃ¡rdÃ¡s folk dress. They recorded the Friedmans and GrÃ¼nbergers as they wanted to be â blueblood aristocrats, socialites and bon vivants, a gentrified elite whose sons bore the names of Magyar kings and saints &#8211; ÃrpÃ¡d, Gyula, LÃ¡szlÃ³, IstvÃ¡n &#8211; and who were fully accepted and absorbed into the Mitteleuropean bloodstream, having cut their last tie with the past and exorcised the shtetl. How could I not suspect these forgeable visas? The counterfeit fantasy captured in these photos was on the cusp of brutal exposure. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In a formal studio portrait (slide 5), 15 members of the Friedman family gathered in formal dress on the occasion of my paternal grandparentsâ âGolden Jubilee,â their 50th wedding anniversary.  Patriarch SÃ¡muel Friedman holds a large metal wreath, each of its golden leaves bearing the name of another member in the extensive family tree. At the far left end of the last row, I see a rail-thin boy, who would have then been 16 years old. He strikes a hand-in-waistcoat Napoleon pose: my father. The photo is dated 1943. More than six decades later, I asked my father to identify the well-dressed people. She slowly ran a finger across the faces as she named them, although not by their names. She was identifying their fates, only a half year after the photograph was taken. âShot in a house. Killed in a brick factory. Died in a cattle car. Gassed in Auschwitz. Gassed in Auschwitz. Gassed. Gassed. Gassed&#8230;â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Only three of the fifteen pictured survived the war. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">An hour into my visit to his small flat in Basel, my 95-year-old great uncle Alexander Gordon, my grandmotherâs only surviving sibling, struggled to his feet â an infected knee caused him great pain â and limped from the room. He returned with a carafe of homemade slivovitz, shot glasses and a manila envelope. He shook the envelope over the coffee table, then plucked nine photographs from the pile. They recorded a bare couple of hours, on May 28, 1942, in the GrÃ¼nberger ancestral village of SpiÅ¡skÃ© Podhradie. The pictures were taken by one of Alexanderâs Christian schoolmates. They weren&#8217;t taken to obscure or pretend; they weren&#8217;t meant to airbrush reality. They were taken, at great risk, to document.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Several of the photos were shot from ground level, others from the vantage of an upper-floor window, providing a vista of the town square. They show a long row of horse-drawn hay wagons, laden with older men, women and children, who are swathed, despite the warmth of the day, in layers of coats, hats, and sweaters, for theyâd only been allowed to bring what they could wear. The perimeter is ringed with spectators, Christian villagers, children playing at their feet. A toddler sits in a window, a kerchiefed granny beside him, his small feet dangling over the ledge above a patch of wall plaster: she has put him there to enjoy the spectacle of the Jews of SpiÅ¡skÃ© Podradhie being carted off to Auschwitz. In one shot, as the wagons pass the monastery, one of the townspeople waved, and a woman in the wagon waved back. My great grandparents would die in Nazi concentration camps (Leopold in Sachsenhausen, Sidonia in RavensbrÃ¼ck), along with 416 of the 436 Jews of SpiÅ¡skÃ© Podradhie. </p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/15/blogs/16-lens-faludi-embed4/16-lens-faludi-embed4-blog480-v2.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/15/blogs/16-lens-faludi-embed4/16-lens-faludi-embed4-blog480-v2.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/15/blogs/16-lens-faludi-embed4/16-lens-faludi-embed4-blog480-v2.jpg" id="100000005099411" width="480" height="304" alt="Jewish villagers are carted off in a wagon, passing beneath a window in SpiÅ¡skÃ© Podradhie, Slovakia. They could only take what they could wear. 1942." class="media-viewer-candidate" data-mediaviewer-src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/15/blogs/16-lens-faludi-embed4/16-lens-faludi-embed4-superJumbo-v2.jpg" data-mediaviewer-caption="Jewish villagers are carted off in a wagon, passing beneath a window in SpiÅ¡skÃ© Podradhie, Slovakia. They could only take what they could wear. 1942." data-mediaviewer-credit="Courtesy of Susan Faludi" /><meta itemprop="height" content="304"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Jewish villagers are carted off in a wagon, passing beneath a window in SpiÅ¡skÃ© Podradhie, Slovakia. They could only take what they could wear. 1942.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Courtesy of Susan Faludi</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Just as the Holocaust gave the ultimate lie to the myth of Jewish assimilation and acceptance, the photographs of that catastrophic day in SpiÅ¡skÃ© Podradhie gave the lie to the earlier family photographs I had viewed. Surely the comfort and complacency of those earlier photos were also intended as protective cover against the fear already building in the lives of Hungarian Jews, no less than the cheer in the photographs of my grandparents&#8217; second honeymoon was meant to paper over their disintegrating marriage. Both were an insistence on illusion. And yet, viewed from the vantage of almost a century later, both sets spoke to me as testament, equally embracing of fact. Even my relativesâ denial of reality in 1936 and 1943 were facts in themselves, faithfully recorded. Even the alibis were evidence.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For all their contrivance, these yellowing photos with serrated borders were a portal more revealing to me than the stacks of tapes and notes Iâd amassed. Here was a whole world finely documented down to the last pocketbook and pocket square. No amount of interviewing could extract such specificity, the odd tiny details that no one would ever be able to summon from memory: My grandmotherâs patent-leather purse dangling incongruously from the arm of her Bedouin escort as he guided her on a donkey ride through the desert. The newspaper crisply folded and tucked under my great-uncle ÃrpÃ¡dâs arm as he strolled down the esplanade. No writing could compete with the minute particularities of these photographs â and no rewriting would change the reality they documented. Here, âfixedâ in these images by chemical bath, was the granular historical record, an archival repository that could not be altered nor avoided. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As I contemplated the snapshots of my great-aunts preening in pearls and flapper dresses or my great uncles resplendent in spats and bowlers, I came up against a contradiction in my own assumptions about the place of image in my fatherâs story. Why do I put such stock in the old photographs my relatives showed me, while dismissing the ones from my own childhood? In their aspiration, they were no less disingenuous than the Ektachrome transparencies of our family camping trips and backyard barbecues, fake grins pasted on our faces. Like the pictures of my immediate family, these older images began as propaganda, elaborate constructions in which the subjects conspired with the photographer to present an image at odds with the cultural reality. But over time, the viewer sees what the sitters cannot, what lies around the bend. Their elaborate tableaux canât fend off what awaits, temporally, off stage. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âBy giving me the absolute past of the pose (aorist), the photograph tells me death in the future,â Roland Barthes famously wrote of the 1865 picture of Lewis Payne in his cell, awaiting execution for the attempted assassination of Secretary of State William H. Seward. He cannot view the image without being overwhelmed by the âcatastropheâ looming in the future, a catastrophe âwhich has already occurred.â As I pored over the photographs of my lost GrÃ¼nberger and Friedman families, their greatest refutation, the eventuality of the Holocaust, alters their message, turns their lies into a kind of helpless honesty. I look at a snapshot of my great-aunt Gabriella and her daughter Marika, cavorting by a lake in the Tatra Mountains. And I see mother and daughter deported to a concentration camp. I see Marika at warâs end, skeletal and tubercular, barely alive in an infirmary in the Tatras. I flip through the photos of my great-uncle ÃrpÃ¡d in his English-tailored suit with his folk-dress bedecked wife and his beribboned daughter. And I am transported to the fall of 1944, husband, wife and child trapped in a house, surrounded by local gendarmerie and SS officers, the house burned down with them in it. The entire import of the picture is in what the picture, and its participants, canât know. How can we condemn ÃrpÃ¡dâs foisting an illusion on us, the viewers, when he is so innocent of the fate we alone are privy to?</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/15/blogs/16-lens-faludi-embed6/16-lens-faludi-embed6-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/15/blogs/16-lens-faludi-embed6/16-lens-faludi-embed6-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/15/blogs/16-lens-faludi-embed6/16-lens-faludi-embed6-blog480.jpg" id="100000005099576" width="480" height="766" alt="ÃrpÃ¡d GrÃ¼nberger strolls along a boardwalk in the Czech spa town of Carlsbad in 1937." class="media-viewer-candidate" data-mediaviewer-src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2017/05/15/blogs/16-lens-faludi-embed6/16-lens-faludi-embed6-superJumbo.jpg" data-mediaviewer-caption="ÃrpÃ¡d GrÃ¼nberger strolls along a boardwalk in the Czech spa town of Carlsbad in 1937." data-mediaviewer-credit="Courtesy of Susan Faludi" /><meta itemprop="height" content="766"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">ÃrpÃ¡d GrÃ¼nberger strolls along a boardwalk in the Czech spa town of Carlsbad in 1937.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Courtesy of Susan Faludi</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">If the GrÃ¼nberger and Friedman photographs began as advertisement, testaments to an assimilation that was in fact fragile and failing, that failure ultimately would restore their veracity. This aspiration was itself a real event, connected to a continuous series of events whose meaning could only be seen in hindsight. As Barthes wrote of the photo of the still alive Payne, âI read at the same time: This will be and this has been.â The viewerâs knowledge of what is to come liberates the photograph from its calculating origins. Here is a record of what could not be known, and so could not be faked. If the picture was meant to obscure what lay just outside the frame at the moment it was shot, what lay outside the frame in the future restores its genuineness, ushers it back into history. With the passage of years, the image gains in mystery, its certainty replaced by question and doubt, and yet, thereby, gains in authority.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My knowledge of the Holocaust transformed my Hungarian familyâs pictures. But such alchemy doesnât require a cataclysmic event. Any event may do, and an accumulation of events decidedly. Every photograph is rehabilitated by time. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the fall of 2015, a relative took on the laborious task of scanning the 5,000 slides of the American Faludi family gatherings and vacations. A week before the first anniversary of our fatherâs death, we gathered in a living room to look at the results projected on a flat-screen TV. As the images flashed by â one disconnected instant after another of an unhappy family faking harmony and bonhomie â I had an uncanny sensation. It was as if I could see through the picture. This artifice, too, was being peeled back and I could now see beneath the film and beyond the frame, to the people weâd become. There were, as always, fewer pictures of my father: he was behind the camera. But when he did appear, leading the way up a mountain slope in the Adirondacks, posing as the sovereign paterfamilias with a proprietary hand on his progenyâs shoulders or his wifeâs (had I snapped some of these shots?), I no longer saw the man the camera recorded. The passage of time had unfrozen his poses, deprived them of their static coercive power. I saw, in every frame of Steve, the ghost of StefÃ¡nie future, the ghost of IstvÃ¡n past, the ghosts of families lost and regained. With the death of my father, our family pictures, like the generations that had preceded them, had begun their conversion from image into narrative. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">They belonged in the book of my father.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><a href="//susanfaludi.com/">Susan Faludi</a> is the Pulitzer Prize-winning author of &#8220;Backlash: The Undeclared War Against American Women.&#8221;</em></p>
<hr />
